# AI Image Generator — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
AI image generation web app with text-to-image and image-to-image workflows.
- Backend: Express (Node.js), no build step, no TypeScript
- Frontend: Bootstrap 5 + vanilla JavaScript
- Providers: DashScope (Alibaba Cloud), Google Gemini, Volcengine (Jimeng)

## Architecture
- `server.js` — Express entry point only, delegates to `src/`
- `src/routes/` — Route handlers (generate, imageToImage, access)
- `src/providers/` — Provider implementations (dashscope, gemini, volcengine)
- `src/middleware/` — Express middleware (auth, CORS, rate limiter, upload, error handler)
- `src/utils/` — Utilities (config, logger, crypto, file, url)
- `public/app.js` — All frontend logic (vanilla JS, ~1280 lines)
- `public/index.html` — Single-page UI

## Code Style
- No TypeScript — this is a plain JavaScript project
- No semicolons (inconsistent in existing code, don't add them)
- Use `const` by default, `let` when reassignment needed
- CommonJS modules (`require`/`module.exports`), no ES modules
- JSDoc comments for exported functions
- Use the existing `log()` utility from `src/utils/logger.js` for debug output

## Key Conventions
- API responses follow `{ imageUrls: string[] }` pattern for image endpoints
- API errors return `{ error: string }` with appropriate HTTP status
- Provider selection via `provider` field: `dashscope` (default), `gemini`, `volcengine`
- Model config lives in `MODEL_CONFIG` and `ALLOWED_SIZES_BY_MODEL` in `src/utils/config.js`
- Volcengine credentials use `AK:SK` format (colon-separated)
- Volcengine `image_urls` must be publicly reachable HTTP(S) URLs, never `data:` URLs

## Don'ts
- Don't introduce TypeScript, bundlers, or build steps
- Don't add frontend frameworks (React, Vue, etc.)
- Don't use ES module syntax (`import`/`export`)
- Don't add test frameworks unless explicitly asked
- Don't modify the `.env.example` structure without good reason
- Don't expose API keys in logs or responses
- Don't remove the brute-force protection on access control

## When Adding Models
1. Add to `MODEL_CONFIG` in `src/utils/config.js`
2. Add size constraints to `ALLOWED_SIZES_BY_MODEL` if applicable
3. Update provider implementation if model has special requirements
4. Update both `README.md` and `README.zh.md`

## When Adding Providers
1. Create `src/providers/newprovider.js`
2. Register in `src/providers/index.js`
3. Add env vars to `.env.example`
4. Update documentation
